// the code on wikibooks
        //creates all of the numbers that would be seen on a calculator
        JButton button1 = new JButton("1");
        button1.addActionListener(al);
        panel.add(button1);
        JButton button2 = new JButton("2");
        button2.addActionListener(al);
        panel.add(button2);
 etc...

how can i raise my IQ?? Some good ways are: 

1) Attempt to expand and increase your vocabulary.  There is a section in Reader's Digest that usually makes this one fun way to learn;
2) Try solving lots of different word puzzles, there are a few good ones on here --they can be either riddles or mathematical puzzles;
3) Try to do puzzles that require 'spatial' thinking or visualizing three dimensional objects;
4) Practice pattern recognition, such as puzzles which ask you to find the next letter or number in a sequence of numbers;
5) Practice doing the "jumble" puzzles or try and create anagrams from other words; and
6) Do a lot of reading and writing!

How to display a message box on the click event of a button in Windows Programming (VC++) ? Hi folks!... I have created a window and a button on it using VC++ 6.0. Now, I want to display a messagebox in response of the click event of button. Please guide me what code to write in the Windows Procedure?. Here is the Windows Procedure:

/* Assume that the main window name is Window1 and button name is Button1 */

LRESULT CALLBACK
WindowProcedure (HWND hwnd, UINT message, WPARAM wParam, LPARAM lParam)
{
    switch (message)                  /* handle the messages */
    {
        case WM_DESTROY:

            PostQuitMessage (0);       /* send a WM_QUIT to the message queue */
            break;


      default:                      /* for messages that we don't deal with */

            return DefWindowProc (hwnd, message, wParam, lParam);
    }

    return 0;
} Hello,

You have to check for the event WM_COMMAND in your switch instruction. And inside that case, check the wParam value (High order byte) of the event to make sure it is a BN_CLICKED event. At that stage, you need to further identify your button using the wParam (Low order byte) of the wParam.

Example:

        case WM_COMMAND: 
          if (HIWORD(wParam) == BN_CLICKED) 
          { 
                switch (LOWORD(wParam)) 
                { 
                    case ID_OF_YOUR_BUTON: 
                        MessageBox(hwnd, "Hello", "Testing", MB_OK);

                        break; 
                } 
          } 
          break; 


I suggest that you take a look to the doc of VC++ on these events, mainly in the Windows SDK doc about Buttons. It is well done with code samples.

Additional note: as you created your button directly on a window instead of within a dialog box, it is very likely that you used a call to the CreateWindow function to create it. In this case, you give the ID number in parameter HMENU hMenu of the function. You may create a Resource ID (it is just an value globally defined with #define) to avoid playing with numbers when you have several controls.

Regards,
Chris.
